Date: Wed, 18 Nov 1998 17:25:30 GMT
From: Tetreault, Gary E., LCDr <dvj0get@jax10.med.navy.mil>

In response to a request from one of the moderators I have this information
to offer. Ambush is permethrin which is a synthetic pyrethroid. It is
widely used as a contact insecticide to control a wide range of
agricultural pests as well as medically important arthropods such as
mosquitoes and ticks. It is commonly used in many military organizations
worldwide to impregnate uniforms to prevent vector-borne disease
transmission due to its repellent properties. Another brand name is Prelude
and they are distributed by Zeneca Corporation. Both of these formulations
are registered for agricultural use. Those used for medically important
arthropods bear different brand names. Pyrethroids in general have low
mammalian toxicities but are very toxic to aquatic life especially fish.
Ambush C is cypermethrin which is the same compound which bears a cyanide
group to promote greater molecular stability therefore increasing residual
activity.
Complete molecular structure information and other properties of these
chemicals can be found in the Global Insecticide Directory First Edition by
W. L. Hopkins.
>From my experience with insecticide toxicology, applied vector control in
the field and use of these compounds, this is REAL bad news for those
ecosystems. Hope this helps.
--
LCDR Gary E. Tetreault, Ph.D
Medical Entomologist
Navy Disease Vector Ecology and Control Center
Jacksonville, Florida
[You can find Permethrin at the following EPA website, but there are many
other places as well listed when searching either under Permethrin or
'Ambush'.
PERMETHRIN (Ambush, Pounce, Astro )
<http://www.epa.gov/ngispgm3/iris/subst/0185.htm>
- Mod.MHJ
