Date: Wed, 18 Nov 1998 15:29:01 +0200
From: R. Horner <rhorner@VETNL.AGRIC.ZA>

I have made enquiries locally in S. Africa because a pesticide called
"Ambush" was marketed here (although I believe stocks are still available
at some agricultural-chemical outlets).
Old formulations ( I don't know how many years ago) were marketed as Ambush
and contained Aldicarb a Carbonate (LD50 for fish 0.56mg/l). However newer
formulations evidently contained Permethrin of the Pyrethroid group with an
LD50 for fish of 0.009mg/l but were still marketed as Ambush!
Both are evidently very toxic to fish so one or both of these pesticides
under the name of "Ambush" could be the culprit. They were used as a
contact insecticide covering a broad range of pests e.g.. leaf and fruit
eating insects on various crops.
--
R. Horner
DEPT OF AGRICULTURE
e-mail: rhorner@VETNL.AGRIC.ZA
[I checked ALDICARB out on the EPA website
Aldicarb
<http://www.epa.gov/ogwdw000/dwh/t-soc/aldicarb.html>
Drinking Water and Health
As part of the Drinking Water and Health pages, this fact sheet is part of
a larger publication:
National Primary Drinking Water Regulations
Technical Factsheet on: ALDICARB AND METABOLITES
NOTE: The MCLs for aldicarb and its metabolites are presently stayed.
Health Effects Summary
Acute: EPA has found aldicarb to potentially cause nausea, diarrhea and
relatively minor neurological symptoms resulting from acute exposures at
levels above the MCL. These effects appear to be rapidly and completely
reversible after exposure. No Health Advisories have been established for
short-term exposures.
Chronic: Aldicarb has the potential to cause neurological effects such as
sweating, pupillary constriction and leg weakness from chronic exposure at
levels above the MCL. These effects are associated with the inhibition of
cholinesterase in blood and nerve tissue.
Cancer: There is inadequate evidence to state whether or not either
aldicarb or its metabolites have the potential to cause cancer from
lifetime exposures in drinking water.
-- and there is more. These symptoms are similar to those quoted for people
eating the poisoned fish.
Gary mentioned the ecosystem damage from this pesticide. After I had
finishing posting yesterday I went back and looked at the East African
maps. There are a large number of rivers there, where also, one must
presume, people fish, bathe, wash clothes, and collect drinking water. See
the next communication. - Mod.MHJ
